<DOCNO> AP900831-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
driftnets meant to catch tuna and squid are 
sweeping up and killing huge numbers of other fish and birds that 
are just thrown away the leaders of a greenpeace foundation 
protest voyage said thursday 
in a news conference following the return of the rainbow warrior 
from a pacific voyage expedition leader ben deeble said the crew 
had found at least 30 species of dolphins birds and fish dead or 
dying in the huge driftnets 
shark alone accounted for 30 percent of the catch in one net 
deeble said 
generally they cut the fins off the sharks and throw the rest 
away said roger grace of auckland new zealand an underwater 
photographer on the mission 
pomfret a small but tasty fish is thrown away by the 
thousands grace said 
the group plans to use videotapes and photographs of marine life 
caught in a plastic monofilament mesh and a 3mile driftnet that it 
seized to campaign for tougher sanctions by the united states and 
united nations against driftnet fishing 
i think the video is the most complete ever shot of the 
driftnet fleet grace said 
deeble said the rainbow warrior crew saw or monitored on radar 
about 200 of the more than 1000 driftnet vessels from japan 
taiwan and korea believed to be operating in the north pacific 
he said plans were being made to unfurl the seized net in the 
downtown area of a us city a process he said would require about 
200 people 
i think thats one reason weve had so much trouble getting 
these driftnets banned he said people cant comprehend the 
size of these things 
the rainbow warrior a 181foot converted trawler departed july 
19 from hawaii with 32 people on a sixweek mission covering more 
than 6000 miles to monitor and protest driftnet fishing for tuna 
and squid 
the nets hang like a curtain more than 30 feet below the surface 
and stretch as far as 35 miles critics say they indiscriminately 
trap and kill fish thousands of marine mammals and 800000 birds a 
year 
at times the protesters brought inflatable motorized launches 
close enough to the fishing vessels to see the faces of the crew 
deeble said 
he said he was invited aboard a taiwanese ship and had dinner 
with the skipper 
it was a very sociable meeting where we discussed our views on 
driftnets deeble said hes looking at changing his technology 
changing to long lines to fish for tuna 
the skipper claimed he caught no whales and rarely found marine 
mammals or birds in the nets although those aboard the rainbow 
warrior saw dolphins and many birds being hauled aboard deeble 
said 
a federal judge in san francisco on tuesday ordered a ban on 
imports of tuna caught by five nations until they can show that 
they are not killing more dolphins than us law allows 
us district judge thelton henderson said the bush 
administration had given foreign fleets too much time to comply 
with a 1988 federal law requiring an embargo of any nation whose 
dolphinkilling rate was more than twice the rate of the us tuna 
fleet 
some commercial fishing fleets deliberately drop their nets on 
dolphins which swim above yellowfin tuna 
</TEXT>
