<TEXT>
leaders of a capitol rally thursday demanded 
that the governor and legislature decriminalize drugs as suggested 
in an advisory panel report parts of which were barred from 
publication by the attorney general 
its censorship and he has the nerve to call himself a 
liberal shouted rally coordinator richard geiselhart we dont 
need a war on drugs we need a war on greed corruption waste and 
stupidity but above all we need a war on hypocrisy 
regina birdsell a spokeswoman for attorney general john van de 
kamp denied the allegation of censorship she said recommendations 
of decriminalization were deleted because they were contained in 
individual members statements and not in a collective panel 
opinion 
the sevenmember commission was created by the legislature to 
study drug abuse and possible remedies birdsell said its report 
explains where people can write for the individual panel members 
opinions she said 
panel members said they recommended that the legislature 
legalize cultivation of marijuana for personal use consider 
decriminalization of other drugs on an individual basis and 
legalize possession of hypodermic needles 
the state panel said current antidrug laws have been 
manifestly unsuccessful in that we are now using more and a 
greater variety of drugs legal and illegal 
many of the 300 people who flocked to the noon rally outside the 
state capitol sported long hair and the tiedyed look of the 1960s 
marijuana smoke wafted through the crowd 
speakers from the national organization to reform marijuana laws 
and other groups said laws against drugs are unconstitutional and 
do more harm than good 
eric garris of mountain view a republican candidate for the 
state assembly drew a huge cheer from the crowd when he said he 
was running for office on a platform of decriminalizing drugs 
all the money time and energy we spend on this 
unconstitutional unworkable hypocrisy via law enforcement courts 
and prisons should be spent to help take the despair out of 
peoples lives through education job training jobs affordable 
housing and medical care geiselhart said 
a large federal raid of marijuana plantations in the mountains 
180 miles northeast of san francisco last month drew criticism from 
many local officials who said it achieved little other than to 
anger residents who said they were mernaced by army troops toting 
automatic weapons 
</TEXT>
