<TEXT>
militant attitudes may be the new fashion 
for many americans but townsfolk here are chewing over a proposal 
to muzzle fighting words on the streets of this college enclave 
the proposal designed to silence racial slurs is part of a 
long line of efforts to promote harmony in a town that has voted 
against every war since 1812 it is already drawing fire from civil 
rights advocates 
this is a caring community its a community of people who 
really have some deep and genuine humane values said paul 
rogers a member of the citizens review committee which has 
written a first draft of the bylaw 
rogers said hes not sure whether the proposal will succeed it 
was inspired by an incident last may in which a white youth 
reportedly shouted racial slurs and knocked a black teenager down 
in amherst a town of about 34000 where residents have marched 
for peace and against war scores of times debating constitutional 
rights is nothing new 
a university of massachusetts at amherst sociology professor 
credited the nature of amherst politics to oldfashioned yankee 
outspokenness at regular and wellattended town meetings and having 
two colleges and the university 
these are people who are familiar with the use of the tongue 
in a situation politically which puts a premium on it said jay 
demerath 
in keeping with tradition a group of residents this month 
marched to the town common to protest us military buildup in 
saudi arabia and suggest that president bush turn to alternate 
methods to resolve the invasion of kuwait 
two years ago a group of senior citizens staged a sitin at the 
university of massachusetts chancellors office to protest research 
on the anthrax disease that they feared could somehow be put to 
militaristic use 
the proposal doesnt give a list of fighting words it 
defines them as those that by their very utterance inflict injury 
upon the person or group of persons to whom they are directed or 
which tend to incite an immediate breach of peace 
john roberts head of the civil liberties union in boston said 
the proposal is a bad idea 
obviously its wellintentioned he said noting that racial 
harassment is on the rise it is ugly and you want to deal with 
it i think this is not a way to deal with it 
rogers said the bylaw doesnt apply to expression of ideas but 
rather to certain offensive forms of speech he likened prosecution 
for shouting racial slurs to a people who get too raucous at a 
latenight party 
if we can regulate hooting and hollering and whistling we can 
certainly regulate these kinds of words that are not protected by 
the constitution he said i know people are going to be 
concerned about protecting free speech and they ought to be 
the proposal may go before a town meeting this fall if it gets 
approval from town counsel alan seewald who declined comment on 
the bylaw thursday 
the bylaws wording comes from a 1942 supreme court case 
chaplinsky vs new hampshire in which a state law prohibiting use 
of fighting words was upheld rogers said in that case a 
selectman had referred to a man as a damn fascist he said 
but roberts said that case applies to specific confrontations 
which are already prohibited under civil rights statutes 
i think theyre going to be in trouble he said 
</TEXT>
