<TEXT>
pope john paul ii arrives 
saturday on the start of a fournation african tour to be climaxed 
by the blessing of a huge costly and controversial basilica in 
ivory coast 
the trip which will take the pope across the bulge of the 
continent will be his 49th foreign tour and his seventh visit to 
africa where declining economies and rapidly rising populations 
spell misery for millions 
as in previous visits the pope is expected to call for 
christian harmony and preach against artificial birth control and 
extramarital sex with its attendant threat of aids a particularly 
deadly scourge in africa 
the world health organization estimates 5 million subsaharan 
africans are infected with the virus that can cause the disease 
that is double the number three years ago 
pope john paul will carry his messages from dar es salaam to 
three other major cities in tanzania an east africa nation of 
about 23 million people most of them are moslems about 20 percent 
of tanzanians subscribe to the roman catholic faith 
after five days in tanzania he will fly to burundi and rwanda 
tiny neighboring and predominantly catholic countries to the 
northwest they are the most densly populated nations in africa and 
their recent history has been marked by clashes between their two 
main ethnic groups the hutus and the tutsis 
the pope will spend two nights each in burundi and rwanda before 
going across the continent to ivory coast where he will end his 
trip sept 10 by consecrating the immense basilica of our lady of 
peace 
rivaling st peters basilica in the vatican in size the 
structure was built by president felix houphouetboigny in his 
hometown of yamoussoukro the government said it cost 133 million 
critics say the real cost could be twice as high and bemoan the 
extravagance in a country undergoing its worst economic crisis in 
30 years of independence only about 11 percent of ivory coasts 11 
million residents are catholics with the majority practicing 
native tribal religions 
houphouetboigny has said he is paying for the basilica out of 
his own pocket published reports have alleged the sale of 16000 
stateowned apartments helped cover the cost 
pope john paul initially refused to bless the basilica which 
was completed last september after four years of work but in june 
the vatican said the pope had relented noting at the same time 
that houphouetboigny had agreed to build a hospital next to the 
basilica 
the basilica is modeled after st peters and is the only one in 
africa with a seating capacity of 7000 people and standing room 
for 11000 more it also is the continents biggest center for 
christian worship 
