<TEXT>
when rats are stuffed with the maximum 
nonlethal dose of a chemical and then develop cancer it may be 
the dose and not the chemical that causes the disease researchers 
say in reports published today 
bruce n ames professor of cell biology at the university of 
california berkeley said governmentsupported cancer tests on 
rats are useless because they depend upon the concept that high 
doses fed to rats over the short rodent lifetime produce the same 
results as very low exposures over a long period of time in humans 
ames said cancer may develop in test rats through a process of 
chronic wounding caused by the dose and not as a direct effect 
of the chemical 
animal cancer tests said ames are conducted at the maximum 
tolerated doses which kill cells and cause nearby cells to divide 
to replace the loss 
each time replacement cells are grown said ames there is a 
risk of a cancer mutation the more cells that are replaced over a 
lifetime the higher the odds of a cell mutating into cancer thus 
he said the cancer may be caused by the dose not by the chemical 
action itself 
government dependence on animal testing for carcinogens is 
pretty much useless for protecting us against low levels of 
chemicals ames said in an interview when you test chemicals 
on rats at very high doses the maximum tolerated doses half of 
them will come out positive develop cancer but the reason is 
that it is killing cells 
such tests he said are chronic wounding experiments and 
chronic wounding is a risk factor for cancer 
ames said that people are unreasonably afraid of synthetic 
chemicals but that humans eat many natural cancercausing 
chemicals in their everyday diet 
he said 77 chemicals that occur naturally in foods have been 
tested on rats at maximum tolerated doses and 37 have been found to 
be carcinogens ames said about the same proportion of carcinogens 
have been found in synthetic chemicals tested 212 out of 350 
a simple cup of coffee said ames has 826 volatile chemicals 
scientists have tested 21 of these chemicals using high doses and 
found that 16 are rodent carcinogens he said 
you get more carcinogens in a cup of coffee than in all of the 
synthetic pesticide residues you absorb in a year said ames 
the scientists said there is a public fear about minute 
quantities in the diet of manmade pesticide residues but he 
noted 999 percent of all pesticides we eat are natural he 
said and 27 out of 52 tested pesticides that occur naturally in 
plants have been found to be rodent carcinogens 
in another paper in science samuel m cohen of the university 
of nebraska college of medicine said that in studies on mice he and 
his collaborators demonstrated that there can be both a dose and a 
chemical effect in developing cancer 
for some chemicals said cohen cancer developed in laboratory 
animals only at very high levels while other chemicals at very low 
doses can trigger mutations that can lead to cancer 
cohen said however that federal law requires all chemicals 
that cause cancer in test animals no matter what the dose to be 
regulated 
a large proportion of the compounds perhaps 50 percent 
listed in the national toxicology program which evaluates 
chemicals cause cancer only at high doses he said 
cohen said the government now classifies chemicals as 
cancercausing or noncancercausing he said there needs to be a 
third category for those compounds that cause cancer only at very 
high doses 
ames said many people demand regulation of synthetic chemicals 
that may be in the environment at only one part per billion this 
he said is not realistic 
one part per billion is one person in all of china he said 
its one drop of vermouth in five tank cars of gin 
people should stop spending all the time and money on such 
trivial levels and start getting after the important cancer 
risks such as smoking preventable infections and high fat 
diets said ames 
sydney green director of toxicological studies for the food and 
drug administration said the views expressed by ames and cohen 
about the value of animal cancer tests are not universally 
accepted but he admitted that some government scientists are 
starting to question past scientific assumptions on cancer tests 
cancers may be caused by dose alone in some cases said green 
but thats uncertain at this point and you cannot extrapolate 
some findings to all substances 
dr bernard d goldstein chairman of the department of 
environmental medicine at the university of medicine and dentistry 
of new jersey said he is convening a panel at the national academy 
of science to examine the use of animal tests in determining human 
cancer risk 
the issues are open to scientific debate he said there 
is a fair amount of interest developing in the issue of maximum 
tolerate dose in evaluating the risk of cancer 
science which published papers by ames and cohen is the 
journal of the american association for the advancement of science 
</TEXT>
