<TEXT>
the persian gulf crisis has placed major 
strains on yemens new unity underscoring the deep ideological 
divide between its oncerival states and jeopardizing relations 
with neighboring saudi arabia 
iraq which has close ties to yemen invaded kuwait only three 
months after the may 22 merger of conservative north yemen and 
marxist south yemen the merger ended nearly three decades of 
rivalry on the southwestern tip of the arabian peninsula 
the new nation of 12 million sits astride the bab el mandeb 
strait the southern gateway to the red sea the sea became more 
important after the 198088 iraniraq spilled into the persian gulf 
western diplomats say the new persian gulf crisis has brought 
out smoldering ideological differences inside yemen there had been 
opposition to the merger from islamic militants in the north and 
diehard marxists in the south 
thousands of yemenis have mounted demonstrations to support 
iraqi president saddam hussein many have reportedly volunteered to 
fight for iraq against the united states and its allies who are 
building up forces in saudi arabia 
gen ali abdullah saleh president of the new yemen republic 
has been put on the spot he is trying to support iraq while 
avoiding a collision with saudi arabia analysts say 
a yemeni newspaper editor speaking on condition of anonymity 
said were in a difficult situation because of our close 
ties with iraq 
saleh the former president of north yemen is one of saddams 
main allies he has refused to join arab moderates in their stand 
against iraq he has also objected to the thousands of us and 
other troops deployed in saudi arabia to counter iraq 
however yemen has also said it will abide by economic sanctions 
imposed by the united nations on iraq 
british sources said yemen could become a staging post for an 
air bridge into iraq to get around the quarantine but aviation 
experts think it unlikely 
some arab diplomats find salehs stance inexplicable and even 
selfdestructive they contend no yemeni leader can afford to 
offend the saudis one of the countrys main benefactors 
but like king hussein of jordan another saddam ally saleh 
faces serious damage to his shaky economy if trade ties with iraq 
are severed 
if iraq comes out victorious in this crisis yemen will look 
good if iraq loses yemen will be in a difficult position in all 
respects politically militarily and economically said one 
arab diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the invasion of kuwait was an economic blow in itself to yemen 
kuwait like saudi arabia provided financial aid and crude oil to 
yemens oil refinery at aden iraq has an agreement to provide 
30000 barrels a day 
