<TEXT>
the nations top sampl regulator says it is 
becoming increasingly difficult to decide which troubled thrifts 
should be taken over by the government 
the job is going to get much tougher timothy ryan director 
of the office of thrift supervision told a news conference 
thursday 
the savings and loans seized by the government in the months 
following the enactment of legislation a year ago were blatantly 
clear cases of failure ryan said 
they were like pornography he said you know it when you 
see it 
now however many troubled sampls are in borderline financial 
situations and much more difficult to identify ryan added 
since the sampl bailout bill became law the governments 
resolution trust corp has taken over 475 ailing institutions 
the office of thrift supervision has recently taken a new 
approach seeking to sell crippled sampls to outside investors while 
they are still under private ownership rather than transferring 
them to the resolution trust corp once they are taken over by the 
government the institutions become more difficult to sell ryan 
noted 
he made the comments as he released an office of thrift 
supervision report showing that the financial conditions of more 
than 200 savings and loans have worsened since the agency made its 
last such report in may 
at least 246 sampls are expected to fail and are likely candidates 
for government takeover the office of thrift supervision said in 
its new report 
if current economic conditions continue or get worse its 
very possible we will see additional deterioration when we report 
again in three months ryan said 
he noted that the sharp increase in oil prices caused by the 
persian gulf crisis had heightened the economic uncertainty the 
thrift industry already suffering from a slowing economy and real 
estate market could be jolted further by rising oil prices 
anything thats bad news for the economy is bad news for the 
sampl cleanup said bert ely a financial institutions analyst in 
alexandria va 
the thrift agencys latest report provides additional evidence 
that we clearly have a deteriorating condition in these 
institutions ely said 
the government has estimated the cost of the savings and loan 
bailout at about 500 billion or 2000 for every us taxpayer 
over the next 30 years 
in its latest quarterly report the office of thrift supervision 
detailed the changes in its classification of the nations sampls 
into four categories of financial health 
there was a modest shifting of sampls from one category to 
another based on financial results for the period from jan 1 
through march 31 the agency said 
the categories are 
group i institutions considered by regulators to be profitable 
and with sufficient capital currently 1175 sampls 
group ii sampls that meet or are expected to meet capital 
requirements 680 
group iii troubled thrifts with poor earnings and low capital 
352 
group iv institutions expected to fail and be taken over by 
the resolution trust corp 246 
the report showed a net decline of 89 in the healthiest sampls 
those in group i 
nearly all the 106 institutions that left the category got 
worse but 17 institutions from lower ratings improved 
there was a net decline of 64 in the shakiest thrifts including 
51 that were seized by the resolution trust corp 
thirtyfour of the shaky sampls improved their position and moved 
into a healthier category mainly by getting new infusions of 
capital from outside investors the office of thrift supervision 
said 
group iv institutions continue to be concentrated in a few 
states texas had the greatest number with 29 followed by florida 
with 25 california 22 illinois 18 new jersey 17 and ohio and 
louisiana 11 each 
in addition thrift assets among the shakiest institutions 
continue to be concentrated in a relatively few large institutions 
with 73 percent of the assets held by 41 sampls with assets of at 
least 1 billion 
