<TEXT>
the labor department is launching a program to 
reduce repetitive motion disorders in the workplace starting with 
plants that process red meat where the rate is 10 times that of 
other industries 
these sometimes crippling disorders account for nearly half of 
all occupational disorders in the united states 
labor secretary elizabeth dole in announcing the initiative 
thursday said the department has drafted with the help of unions 
and meat industry representatives a set of guidelines to help 
companies deal with the problem 
its really a common sense approach that combines proper 
workplace engineering job design effective employee training and 
education she said 
the guidelines will be voluntary but companies that agree to 
follow them would avoid special inspections targeted at repetitive 
motion problems beginning in january 1991 she said 
we think its a positive agreement said j patrick boyle 
president of the american meat institute which represents 450 meat 
processing and packing companies that make up about 95 percent of 
the red meat industry 
repetitive motion trauma results from repeated motion or awkward 
positioning of the hand arm back or leg for extended periods 
disorders include lower back injuries tendon disorders and carpal 
tunnel syndrome a nerve disorder of the hand and wrist 
in the meat industry which employs about 140000 nationwide 
workers often perform repetitive motions such as cutting and 
lifting 
in 1988 an estimated 20000 to 25000 meatpackers and 
processers were among an estimated 140000 us workers reported to 
have repetitive motion disorders officials said experts believe 
that half or fewer of the disorders actually are reported 
the labor department is beginning the process of drafting rules 
to cover workers in all industries but she said that could take 
years to complete 
in the meantime she said the guidelines for the red meat 
industry are an effort to eliminate as many illnesses as possible 
as quickly as possible 
the guidelines will be sent to each red meat plant in the united 
states 
the 16 largest companies which each have more than 1000 
employees and later the approximately 20 companies that have more 
than 500 workers at a single plant will be asked to agree to adopt 
the guidelines said alan mcmillan deputy assistant labor 
secretary 
that would cover more than half of the workers in the beef and 
pork industries he said 
smaller businesses will be able to request training and other 
technical assistance from the occupational safety and health 
administration 
companies that agree to the guidelines will be monitored and 
osha will conduct inspections in response to complaints but the 
companies would not be cited for violations if monitoring showed 
they were making progress in eliminating repetitive motion hazards 
mrs dole said 
some recommended solutions to repetitive motion problems include 
proper design of work stations employee training slowing 
production rates limiting overtime and rotating workers among 
different jobs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

