<TEXT>
researchers have identified a chemical compound 
contaminating some batches of the food supplement ltryptophan 
which has killed 27 and sickened hundreds 
the compound was discovered during chromatography tests of 
contaminated ltryuptophan the national centers for disease 
control said thursday 
cdc researchers said they still dont know exactly how the 
contaminant got in the product they also have yet to determine 
whether the chemical compound is itself the cause of the illness or 
just a marker of another substance 
another advance in tracing the cause of the rare blood disorder 
called eosinophiliamyalgia syndrome or ems was reported at the 
national institute of mental health in bethesda md a model of the 
disorder was reproduced there in rats 
nationwide cdc has received reports of 1536 cases of ems 
which has been linked to consumption of ltryptophan an amino 
acid but the cdc said the number of cases may be higher as many 
ems cases dont meet the official case definition but still appear 
to be related to ltryptophan 
maybe our figures might be missing half the cases id say 
3000 to 5000 is a reasonably good estimate said dr edwin 
kilbourne chief of health studies at the cdcs center for 
environmental health 
twentyseven patients have died from ems whose symtoms include 
pains fever rash and shortness of breath 
the food and drug administration ordered all ltryptophan 
products off the market this spring the products were sold through 
health food stores as a remedy for conditions including weight 
problems sleeplessness and depression 
the chemical compound is known as a ditryptophan aminal of 
acetaldehyde it was identified in trace amounts in 
chromatography tests of 50 lots of ltryptophan produced by the 
implicated manufacturer said dr larry needham toxicology chief 
for the cdcs center for environmental health 
reports have identified the manufacturer as japans showa denko 
kk 
its an impurity needham said its not supposed to be in 
the product 
lab investigations have found no signs of bacteria or viruses 
contaminating the product but data indicate that implicated 
ltryptophancontaining products were contaminated with the 
chemical compound the cdc said after nearly a year of 
investigation 
a new england journal of medicine report earlier this month 
concluded showa denko whose product has been linked to most cases 
made two changes in manufacturing which could have caused the 
problem introduction of a new strain of genetically altered 
bacteria and alteration of its filtering process 
