justify any military action against iraq according to 
administration sources quoted by the los angeles times 
the administration also might make the capture of saddam and his 
key advisers for trial one of the objectives of the us buildup in 
the persian gulf officials told the times 
some legal action has to be taken both because we have a 
right to bring him to justice and to deter him from further 
violations said an administration official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
in the short term administration officials said the preparation 
of charges was intended to deter saddam from taking further action 
against thousands of civilian hostages in iraq and kuwait 
the report did not state whether plans were being made for 
saddams capture or in what venue the administration would want to 
try the iraqi leader 
among the alleged violations cited by officials is that saddam 
has waged a war of aggression by invading kuwait on aug 2 that 
charge formed the basis of the war crimes trials of nazi leaders in 
nuremberg after world war ii 
other possible allegations include using chemical weapons 
taking hostages kidnapping diplomats violating embassies and 
holding captives at military installations officials said 
those actions constitute violations of the 1949 geneva 
convention and the 1973 new york convention protecting embassies 
diplomats and their families the officials said 
saddam has really put himself in a situation of dire jeopardy 
by using civilians said abraham d sofaer a former state 
department legal adviser its a clear violation of the laws of 
war to intentionally expose civilians for military purposes is a 
clear violation of the geneva convention 
