<TEXT>
the persian gulf crisis is occurring in a 
region that has become the worlds leading destination for 
increasingly sophisticated weaponry from tanks to fighter planes 
and smart missiles 
the arms that flowed into the areas two leading buyers iraq 
and saudi arabia during the last 15 years are now aimed across 
their common border in a dispute that in some ways echoes the 
nowdiffused cold war 
both we and the soviets thought we were creating allies 
forging relationships on our team in the global bipolar power 
struggle said michael t klare a professor of peace and world 
security studies at hampshire college in massachusetts 
but thats not what they thought they were doing said 
klare who wrote a prescient article in may about the emergence of 
regional superpowers like iraq at no point did any of these 
countries think they were playing on either team they have their 
own agenda 
saudi arabia and iraq received nearly onethird of more than 
300 billion in arms sold to third world countries from 1982 
through 1989 according to a congressional research service 
analysis of us intelligence data 
the united states and the soviet union accounted for more than 
60 percent of that total weapons trade 
the soldiers of iraqi president saddam hussein carry soviet 
