earned a special place in the german unification treaty signed 
friday 
the sorbs who number about 100000 and live in east germanys 
spree forest asked for legal protection of their unique culture 
and got it 
the preservation and continuation of sorb culture and of sorb 
traditions will be guaranteed members of the sorb people have the 
freedom to preserve their language in public life states one 
part of the treaty 
the sorbs are native residents of a remote swath of east germany 
stretching 56 miles north of the czechoslovak border centuries ago 
their marshy wooded homeland was called lusatia 
they are colorful in customs and in dress the traditional way 
for sorbs to get to their fields or visit neighboring villages is 
in long thin wooden boats that are pushed with a pole along small 
waterways crisscrossing the spree forest 
many sorbs are farmers but eelfishing is also a customary 
livelihood 
the sorbs withstood german invasions in the sixth eighth 10th 
and 12th centuries ultimately german invaders swallowed up their 
homeland but not their customs until adolf hitler ordered their 
language not be spoken 
east germanys communist rulers generally allowed the sorbs to 
preserve their ways and actually helped the sorb culture thrive by 
virtually sealing off much of east germany from western influences 
now with east germany opened up to the outside world and 
westerners flooding in the sorbs worry their unique traditions 
could be endangered 
