<TEXT>
an ancient burial cave containing the 
mummified remains of more than 30 people has been found in the 
aleutians the discovery is being called one of the most important 
in alaska in years 
a volunteer working for the us fish and wildlife service 
discovered the cave in june while looking for fox dens on an 
uninhabited island chuck diters the agencys regional 
archaeologist said friday foxes are being eradicated to protect a 
rare species of goose 
this discovery is unquestionably one of the most important 
archeological finds in alaska in a halfcentury said diters 
wellpreserved artifacts found in the cave include weapons 
household goods and artwork and some toys that were buried with 
children 
the location was not disclosed 
they were real closedmouth about it very careful in order to 
protect it from pot hunters they didnt even radio information 
about the find we didnt know about it until they got back to adak 
in june 
since then archaeologists have been studying the caves 
contents 
the aleut corp the regional native corporation that has rights 
to the remains and artifacts under the alaska native claims 
settlement act authorized their removal to the university of 
connecticut and vassar college for further examination 
all will be returned to alaska when the studies are complete to 
become the property of the aleut corp diters said 
this does not represent the discovery of any new culture he 
said but it gives us a chance to look at a previously 
uninvestigated area that has the full range of its occupation 
materials in a single area not previously disturbed 
most sites in the aleutians and in other areas of the state 
are overlaid by other cultures so theyre fragmentary through 
other disturbance with this weve got a chance to see a more 
tightly focused and cleared cultural picture 
the last previous work in this area was done in the 30s in a 
hasty fashion and without regard for information that can be 
determined in a careful controlled examination diters said 
scientists suspect the area around the cave was a village and 
they hope to expand their investigation next year 
its rare we get the opportunity to excavate the burial and 
village site in same situation diters said 
although not totally preserved the human remains had been 
ceremonially mummified and wrapped for burial in finely woven grass 
mats in accordance with aleut burial rites diters said 
we found bodies of both sexes and all ages from less than 
oneyearold infants to old toothless elders said lucy lewis 
johnson an archaeologist on the faculty of vassar in poughkeepsie 
ny 
this cave has given us a priceless glimpse of a realm of 
culture she said it is unique not just because of the number 
of bodies but also because it has so many well preserved organic 
artifacts 
that includes a finely carved wooden sculpture of a whale or 
fish with a sea otter or small human on its snout and a bird in 
flight at the tip of its jaw 
