<TEXT>
milwaukee county officials trying to reduce 
welfare fraud are considering a unique program that would leave 
recipients with little discretionary cash 
the program would require direct payment of welfare recipients 
housing utility and food bills through vouchers electronic fund 
transfers or governmentappointed third parties 
the plans sponsor said he hoped the program would end abuses of 
aid to families with dependent children in which cash benefits are 
spent wrongly by adults and children are left to suffer 
im not embarking on a course of welfare bashing said 
county supervisor richard d nyklewicz im trying to be a 
responsible representative and ensure the money is used for its 
intended purpose 
but a lawyer for legal action of wisconsin an advocacy group 
said she would also oppose the cashless system 
i think its terrible said shirin cabraal its a real 
patronizing type of attitude toward welfare recipients the whole 
idea that welfare recipients are not capable of handling welfare 
benefits 
if approved by milwaukee county nyklewiczs experiment still 
would need state and federal approval 
the milwaukee county social services committee began its review 
of the proposal this week but delayed a decision until next month 
supervisor elizabeth coggsjones asked for the delay to allow 
the county health and social services department to research 
whether there are viable alternatives that wont take free choice 
away from welfare recipients 
im not a proponent of cashless voucher systems i think its 
not true welfare reform she said true welfare reform is 
educating people and training them to get decent jobs with decent 
wages and benefits 
the federal government already permits the use of welfare 
benefit vouchers to pay vendors like landlords and utility 
companies but only in cases where a recipient has mismanaged funds 
or needs special assistance 
gary ashcraft director of the division of program evaluation 
for the us department of health and human services in washington 
said the milwaukee program would be the nations first to not use 
cash for general welfare in ordinary cases 
jason turner director of the departments office of family 
assistance said he disliked the idea because welfare recipients 
generally should receive the money and make their own decisions 
with it 
gov tommy g thompson who has initiated two state welfare 
experiments said he would support the milwaukee county plan and 
help obtain the necessary state and federal approval 
if we can have this cashless system set up to assist people 
better then from what people tell me its a step in the right 
direction he said 
thompson urged approval in 1987 of wisconsins learnfare 
program which allows the state to cut a welfare familys monthly 
afdc benefits if one or more of its teenagers have been 
consistently absent from school 
the program was suspended in milwaukee this summer by a federal 
judge who said families were being unfairly sanctioned by 
inaccurate attendance records in milwaukee schools 
the thompson administration also has experimented with a program 
called workfare which requires welfare recipients to participate 
in job training or work parttime to keep their benefits 
milwaukee county the states largest with a population of about 
970000 distributes 64 million per month in food stamps and 
166 million in afdc benefits 
one afdc recipient calvin hopson 43 said he believed there 
was too much mismanagement in a way i think vouchers would 
help hopson said 
