prices farmers get for raw products declined 
13 percent from july to august but the overall commodity price 
index was still 34 percent above a year ago the agriculture 
department said friday 
lower prices were reported for hogs grapefruit and corn higher 
prices for cattle eggs and milk offset part of the decline for the 
other commodities the departments agricultural statistics board 
said in its preliminary report 
beef cattle prices were at a record level and milk prices set a 
record for the month of august 
most prices are midaugust averages which will be revised next 
month for example the latest report showed july prices rose 07 
percent instead of being unchanged as the report indicated a month 
ago 
no new figures were released to show how much farmers pay to 
meet expenses those are adjusted quarterly and last months 
report showed the pricespaid index was up 05 percent from april 
when the previous estimate was made 
meanwhile department economists say consumer food prices are 
going up 5 percent to 7 percent this year compared with 58 
percent in 1989 the most since 1981 
a new forecast this week put 1990 net cash income of farmers at 
a record in the range of 59 billion to 63 billion up about 
onetenth from last year the previous high was 572 billion in 
1988 
net cash income is the money nationally that farmers have left 
from gross cash income during a calendar year after deducting cash 
expenses it includes government payments and proceeds from crops 
grown previously but sold during the year 
another method taking into account changes in inventories 
depreciation and other allowances during a calendar year shows 
that 1990 net farm income may be in a range of 47 billion to 52 
billion compared with 47 billion last year 
based on the preliminary figures the august price index for all 
crops was down 31 percent from july and 16 percent below a year 
earlier both wheat and feed grains were down from july while 
soybeans were up 
the august index for livestock and products was up 06 percent 
from july and 81 percent above the yearearlier average 
compared with july higher prices for beef cattle calves 
milk and eggs more than offset lower prices for hogs and 
broilers the report said 
