<TEXT>
an increasingly frustrated nasa will 
try again to launch columbia on wednesday if a broken electronic 
part used for one of the telescopes aboard the shuttle can be 
repaired easily 
workers entered the shuttle cargo bay friday to try to find 
whats wrong with an electronic box at the base of an xray 
telescope one of four in the missions 150 million astro 
observatory 
the space agency late thursday called off a scheduled saturday 
launch after spending the day fruitlessly trying to communicate 
with the telescope inside the shuttles cargo bay the broken part 
is believed to have caused the loss of contact 
it was the second time the columbia countdown had been halted 
the first launch attempt in late may was scrubbed because of a 
hydrogen fuel leak 
the last space shuttle mission was in april the current lapse 
is the longest between shuttle flights since the hiatus following 
the 1986 challenger disaster 
any time we get close and dont go like a kid going to the 
carnival were frustrated and were anxious to get going said 
william lenoir head of nasas space flight program but were 
not going until were ready i think were getting awfully close to 
ready 
the latest problem appears to involve a line driver a component 
of the electronic box which routes electrical power and telemetry 
between the orbiter and the xray telescope said lennard fisk 
nasas chief scientist if that is the case a cable can be easily 
installed to a second line driver in the unit he said 
the launch will be delayed until friday or saturday however if 
the entire electronic box has to be replaced fisk said nasa 
expects to know the extent of the problem by saturday afternoon 
columbias seven astronauts plan to remain at kennedy space center 
until then 
were calmly taking our time and when its ready were going 
to go fly lenoir said 
saturdays launch also had been threatened by a problem with a 
middeck instrument that measures acceleration and vibration said 
launch director bob sieck the instrument failed to activate 
properly during the countdown and probably will have to replaced 
four astronomers aboard columbia will operate astros three 
ultraviolet telescopes during the nine to 10day flight the 
observatory will probe some of the hottest objects in the universe 
including a comet and a supernova 
the latest delay is not expected to affect astros observing 
schedule fisk said but it is the latest in a series of 
embarrassments for nasa 
atlantis classified pentagon mission was delayed from july to 
november after the shuttle was found to be leaking hydrogen and 
the entire threeshuttle fleet temporarily was grounded 
in addition to the leaking shuttles the space agency has spent 
the summer contending with the hubble space telescopes flawed 
mirror and the occasional loss of contact with the venusorbiting 
magellan spacecraft 
nasa had hoped to launch nine shuttle flights this year only 
three have gone the last one being discoverys trip in april with 
hubble 
discovery is scheduled to be moved to another launch pad on 
sunday to await an october flight with the sunprobing ulysses 
satellite columbia has until sept 14 to lift off otherwise it 
will be forced to wait until after discoverys flight lenoir said 
nasa must launch discovery between oct 5 and 23 to take 
advantage of the alignment of earth the sun and jupiter whose 
gravitational field will slingshot ulysses back to the sun the 
next opportunity for launch will not be for another 13 months 
as far as the leaks lenoir said the launch team is confident of 
columbias new hydrogen lines 
he also said it now appears atlantis has the same type of leaks 
as columbia engineers initially believed atlantis leaks were in a 
different place than the ones on columbia 
nasa will rely more on visual evidence of hydrogen leaks during 
fueling for future flights and use different criteria for sensors 
lenoir said 
</TEXT>
