<TEXT>
scientific organizations from eight countries 
have signed an agreement to found a committee for cooperation and 
information exchange in research on the north polar region 
the groups all from countries with territories in the arctic 
zone formally agreed this week to found a nongovernmental 
organization to be called the international arctic science 
committee the national academy of sciences said friday 
signing the agreement were organizations from canada denmark 
finland iceland norway sweden the soviet union and united 
states the founding articles were signed at a remote scientific 
outpost in resolute canada 
the national academy of sciences the us organization that 
signed the agreement will help coordinate the research of 
countries that maintain active arctic science programs and help 
integrate arctic studies with the research on the global 
environment 
membership in the iasc is open to all countries with significant 
arctic science programs group said in a statement representatives 
from four other countries had observers at the meeting 
improved relations between the east and west and a greater 
importance given to arctic cooperation between the soviet union and 
the united states were decisive factors in reaching the 
agreement the statement said 
scientific interest in both the north and south polar regions 
has grown in recent times because of concern about global warming 
the statement said changes in the earths average temperature 
caused by the socalled greenhouse effect are expected to be 
greatest in the polar areas 
experts believe that global warming could lead to shrinkage of 
the polar sea ice fields the thawing of permanently frozen soils 
melting of glaciers and ice sheets and a worldwide rise in the sea 
level 
arctic conditions also influence global weather patterns and 
ocean circulation the statement said 
organizations signing the agreement were the academy of 
finland the danish commission for scientific research in 
greenland the icelandic council of science the interdepartmental 
committee on international science and technology relations of 
canada the norwegian academy of sciences and letters the royal 
swedish academy of sciences the ussr academy of sciences and 
the national academy of sciences 
