<TEXT>
a study found that people near the three 
mile island nuclear power plant have a higher risk of some cancers 
but saw no solid evidence that radiation from the plants 1979 
accident was a factor its authors said friday 
the study which reviewed hospital records of 160000 people 
living within 10 miles of the plant also found no significant 
relation between exposure to radiation during the accident and 
childhood cancers or leukemia 
the study which used data from 1975 through 1985 appears to 
corroborate previous government reports which found no detrimental 
health effects linked to the accident which damaged the unit 2 
reactor and led to a 1 billion cleanup 
overall the pattern of results does not provide convincing 
evidence that radiation releases from the three mile island nuclear 
facility influenced cancer risk during the limited period of the 
followup the study concluded 
but two authors of the report columbia university 
epidemiologist maureen hatch and three mile island public health 
fund investigator dr jan beyea acknowledged that some findings 
showed increased cancer risks they said those risks did not appear 
linked to the accident 
for example there were 34 cases of lymphoma cancer in 198485 
other than hodgkins disease that indicated a twofold increase in 
the risk for residents who were living in the areas north and west 
of the plant where the highest radiation doses occurred at the 
time of the accident the report said 
but previous studies have not linked lymphoma cancer with 
radiation even in high doses the report pointed out 
the study was funded by a 700000 grant from the health fund 
which was established by a 1981 court order to pay for the study of 
public health issues related to the accident the findings were 
published in the september issue of the american journal of 
epidemiology 
the study also found there were 1529 total cases of cancer 
excluding lung cancer from 1975 to 1979 that figure jumped to 
2391 from 1981 to 1985 ms hatch said the disparity might have 
been caused by faulty recordkeeping at hospitals which were just 
beginning to computerize records in the mid1970s 
another increase in risk was noted for lung cancer but the 
report concluded that an effect of plant emissions in producing 
the unusual patterns of lung cancer and nonhodgkins lymphoma 
appears unlikely and alternative explanations need to be 
considered the effect of smoking was one explanation cited for 
lung cancer 
the report was greeted with skepticism by some members of the 
community around tmi located about 10 miles south of harrisburg on 
an island in the susquehanna river 
kay pickering a spokeswoman for three mile island alert a 
citizens group said a more exhaustive study was needed before 
residents could be sure their health was not affected 
marjorie m aamodt who helped conduct a 1984 survey of 
residents in the area said the study should have included clinical 
examinations of people who suffered illnesses at the time of the 
accident 
a 1985 state health department study the first of its kind 
after the accident found no pattern of increased cancer cases or 
deaths but did turn up isolated instances of higherthanexpected 
cancer cases in several communities downwind from the plant the 
new study dismissed those cases as statistically insignificant 
a 1984 survey conducted by mrs aamodt and her husband found 
cancer deaths up to seven times higher than expected in sections of 
newberry and fairview townships near the plant the health 
department judged that survey invalid because it appeared to focus 
on streets where cancer victims lived 
there are about 2000 lawsuits pending against the owners of tmi 
for alleged health effects stemming from the accident 
the accident occurred after a combination of human and 
mechanical errors allowed protective cooling water to drain from 
the reactor some of the reactors uranium fuel rods melted and 
radioactive gases and particles were released to the environment 
it was the worst accident at a commercial nuclear power plant in 
the united states 
</TEXT>
