<DOCNO> AP900831-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
people with heart disease who exercise in 
air laden with carbon monoxide are likely to suffer irregular 
heartbeats a precursor to sudden death according to a published 
study 
the research by the university of north carolina and the 
environmental protection agency expands on earlier findings that 
even low levels of carbon monoxide are dangerous for the estimated 
9 million americans with heart disease 
an editorial accompanying the report in saturdays annals of 
internal medicine said the epas carbon monoxide regulations should 
be better enforced rather than tightened 
about onethird of the us population almost 78 million 
people live in areas that exceed the outdoor carbon monoxide 
limits of 9 parts per million in eight hours or 35 parts per 
million in one hour the epa says 
carbon monoxide reduces the bloods ability to carry oxygen by 
binding to hemoglobin a protein that ferries oxygen from the lungs 
to the heart the pollutant changes the proteins structure to a 
form called carboxyhemoglobin which cant transport oxygen 
the average level of carboxyhemoglobin in nonsmokers is about 
15 percent while the epa regulations are designed to protect 
against a 3 percent level 
the study examined the heartbeats of 41 nonsmokers with heart 
disease who were exposed to two concentrations of carbon monoxide 
before riding exercise bicycles the study was designed to raise 
the level of carboxyhemoglobin to either 4 percent or 6 percent a 
level commonly found in smokers 
at levels of 6 percent the number of multiple irregular 
heartbeats during exercise was three times greater than normal the 
researchers found the heart irregularities can lead to sudden 
death 
the researchers were surprised to find that the volunteers 
showed little effect on their heartbeat at the 4 percent level 
said the lead author dr david s shep of the university of north 
carolina 
but shep cautioned against politicizing the studys findings 
saying that previous studies found that men with blocked arteries 
suffered chest pains while exercising when exposed to levels of 
only 2 percent carboxyhemoglobin 
the fact that we didnt find effects at 4 percent shouldnt be 
taken to mean that we should liberalize our air quality 
regulations he warned 
the editorialists dr sandra walden and dr sidney gottlieb of 
the johns hopkins university school of medicine said the studys 
implications for environmental regulations are complex 
a simplistic solution may appear to be tighter restrictions of 
automobile and other industrial emissions however without equally 
serious consideration of enforcement issues the effect of tighter 
restrictions alone would be limited they wrote 
gottlieb said it was frightening that low levels of carbon 
monoxide can apparently be dangerous to so many people with heart 
problems or heart disease 
jim raub a health scientist for the epa said the study will 
contribute to a current evaluation of carbon monoxide regulations 
he said the studys results will add to the debate over whether 
tighter restrictions are needed to protect more people 
people who exercise outdoors whether afflicted with heart 
disease or not should exercise early or late in the day to avoid 
peaks in the airs level of carbon monoxide and shun 
trafficcongested areas said dr phillip marone director of 
thomas jefferson universitys sports medicine center 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

