frank dunlop runs the worlds biggest 
arts festival in edinburgh on a budget this year of 35 million 
pounds 66 million and expects to balance the books 
barbara neville a computer systems analyst from london brings 
her talents as a storyteller to the threeweek festival at a cost 
of 1500 pounds 2850 from her own pocket 
this year dunlop has rudolf nureyev the bolshoi opera the san 
francisco symphony orchestra and paintings by paul cezanne but 
some critics still complain there arent enough big names 
this is not a festival for betsy bloomingdale diamonds and a 
different dress every night with a house in the alps outside 
salzburg dunlop said in an interview the festival is for 
everyone and our tickets are the cheapest if we went for just big 
names we could find ourselves spending 100000 pounds 190000 on 
three days of rehearsals for one orchestra 
the prestige of appearing at the festival encourages some 
governments to subsidize visits by their arts companies 
we couldnt do the program without that support dunlop 
readily acknowledged 
taxpayers commercial sponsors and the box office make up his 
budget 
