<TEXT>
in rome gasoline has shot to almost 5 a gallon 
since iraq invaded kuwait many swedes are paying 75 to fill er 
up 
but analysts say despite exorbitant price hikes western europe 
will be less damaged than the united states by rising energy prices 
the picture that i draw is of a europe that is not as 
dependent on oil as it was at the beginning of this decade said 
peter bogin the assistant director for oil markets at cambridge 
energy research associates in paris 
oil and gas prices have increased worldwide since iraq invaded 
kuwait on aug 2 the price of a barrel of light sweet crude hit 
32 in new york before receding this week following opecs 
decision to boost production to make up for lost iraqi and kuwaiti 
oil 
analysts expect the oil crisis to push up inflation and slow 
growth in western europe but there is little talk about an 
imminent recession as in the united states thats because of the 
factors in europes favor relatively good economic health a drop 
in oil use and the cheapness of the dollar the currency used for 
oil purchases 
western europe and the united states import about the same 
amount of crude oil per person bogin said but in addition to the 
imports americans use an equal amount of domestically produced oil 
were gas guzzlers thats the problem said paul horne an 
american who is chief international economist for smith barney 
international in paris 
europeans have always relied less on cars than americans with 
traditionally lower incomes europeans bought fewer more 
gasefficient cars many governments developed extensive train 
systems 
western europe was still hit hard economically by the energy 
crises of 197374 and 197880 but when gas prices started falling 
many governments kept them artificially high through taxation 
aiming in part to cut consumption 
thus even though many western europeans now are as wealthy as 
americans they dont buy cars that are as big or use them as much 
people cant afford to run a cadillac when the price of gas 
goes to a dollar a liter said jacques michaux the deputy head 
for oil and gas at the european communitys energy division there 
are roughly four liters to a gallon 
in italy for example the bestselling car is the compact fiat 
uno which gets about 47 miles to the gallon at 55 mph 
the most popular us car last year was the midsized sedan 
honda accord which gets about 28 mpg on the highway 
in the past decade western europe has also followed the united 
states in slashing its reliance on oil to produce electricity 
france for example has become the worlds leader in reliance 
on nuclear energy getting more than 80 percent of its electricity 
from nuclear plants 
england and west germany have switched to coal to produce some 
of their power while norway exports electricity from its numerous 
hydroelectric plants 
one glaring exception is italy which still gets nearly half its 
electricity from oil 
european industries have made a huge effort to reduce their 
use of oil said michaux he cited steel cement petrochemical and 
paper plants in particular 
the effects are dramatic between 1980 and 1989 france became 
35 percent less oilreliant while england dropped 37 percent and 
west germany 31 percent according to figures compiled by the 
cambridge energy research associates 
by comparison the united states became 20 percent less 
oilintensive in that period 
while western europe is not expected to suffer the economic 
damage it did from previous oil crises there is still concern 
about price hikes at the pump since the aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
the increases have varied widely ranging from no rise in pump 
prices in portugal to 5 percent in italy to as much as 22 percent 
in greece 
the increases have prompted france to slap on price controls and 
west germany and britain to investigate oil companies pricing 
policies italy plans to freeze prices of petroleum products for 
three months naf norways largest auto association boycotted 
shell stations for a week after they became the first to raise 
prices before old supplies had been used up 
however many europeans have also grown used to stiff gas costs 
i didnt like it obviously said one man as he filled his 
gray fiat uno at a rome gas station but here the price is 
always going up for different reasons but its always going up 
