<DOCNO> AP900831-0244 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the government steeply increased 
utility rates friday and announced plans to lay off thousands of 
public employees in an effort to cut the financial deficit and 
stimulate an economy in deep recession 
hours earlier president carlos menem asked his countrymen to 
have patience with his 13monthold government which took office 
amid hyperinflation and recession 
economy minister antonio gonzalez said many public employees 
under contract would be laid off beginning in september and civil 
servants would be forced to retire early he gave no figure but 
analysts said the total would reach at least 80000 of a public 
workforce of 3 million 
gonzalez said gasoline prices for cars would go up 35 percent as 
of saturday and other public service rates would increase by an 
average 12 to 15 percent or about the rate of inflation projected 
for august 
he said his ministry will oversee the 13 biggest state 
companies which until now reported to the public works ministry 
and the major factories that until now were part of the defense 
ministry 
the state airline railroad telphone and other companies must 
pay their debts from their revenue and budgets because the central 
bank no longer will make up their deficits he announced 
the central bank will require all banks that owe it money to 
clear up their accounts those that cannot will be forced out of 
business he said 
argentina is undertaking a profound transformation of the 
public sector gonzalez said in a address on state radio and tv 
the goal is a state that is austere and efficient and 
capable of all the tasks of a modern state 
the measures were imposed by decree 
menems solution to argentinas economic straits has been to 
reduce the role of the state in the economy and spur private 
enterprise 
were looking from the national government to restructure the 
state to do serious surgery on the state and for that sacrifice 
and understanding are needed menem told reporters the party 
is over 
the menem government removed controls on prices and foreign 
exchange linked public service rates and their costs reduced 
import tariffs and export taxes cut the 1990 budget by 4 billion 
encouraged foreign investment and partially deregulated the oil 
industry 
the government also has proposed tax reform and reorganizing the 
central bank to make it more independent 
as a result the increase in the monthly cost of living fell to 
near single digits in july from 197 percent 12 months earlier the 
exchange rate has held steady for six months the fiscal deficit 
narrowed 
the cost has been a deep recession however unemployment and 
underemployment at a combined rate of 18 percent is a record real 
wages have not kept up with inflation many families are hard 
pressed to make ends meet 
wage strikes and public protests about the pending sale of 
public firms like the airline and phone company are increasing 
teachers have boycotted public classrooms for a month 
political leaders openly worry about the prospect of social 
upheaval such as the food riots of may and june 1989 which killed 
16 people wounded more than 200 and resulted in nearly 2500 
arrests 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

